& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Pancreas transplant (PT) improves quality of life and longevity in patients with diabetes by restoring endocrine function, eliminating insulin use, and reducing long-term complications. The benefits of PT must be weighed against the risks, including postsurgical complications and long-term immunosuppression. Surgical advances and improved immunosuppression regimens in the past 2 decades have led to improved patient and allograft survival rates. Imaging a PT can be challenging because of the complex postsurgical anatomy and difficulty distinguishing the PT from adjacent bowel, particularly at US. Nevertheless, US is the first-line imaging modality for evaluating the allograft and vasculature for complications. Contrast-enhanced US is a useful next step to evaluate blood flow to the allograft when Doppler US findings are inconclusive. CT with oral contrast material is preferred for evaluating suspected bowel complications and is useful for evaluating fluid collections. CT angiography is a rapid way to evaluate vasculature and bleeding complications if iodinated contrast material is not contraindicated. MRI can be used as a problem-solving tool to further evaluate complications, particularly when iodinated contrast material is contraindicated or radiation risk is a concern. Ferumoxytol-enhanced MRI is advantageous for evaluating transplant vasculature because of the prolonged intravascular state of the contrast material. It is important for radiologists to understand the spectrum of normal imaging appearances of the pancreas allograft, as well as various posttransplant complications, to provide optimal care. The authors discuss surgical techniques and the anatomy of PT, review imaging evaluation, and describe complications.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2025</div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/large/rg.240180.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240180">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240180">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Donor and recipient pancreas arterial anatomy, including the regional arteries (arrows) and the sites of surgical ligation for donor pancreas harvest and donor Y-graft harvest (dashed lines). CIA = common iliac artery. (A) The head and uncinate process of the native pancreas are supplied by the superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries, which arise from the gastroduodenal artery and SMA, respectively, whereas the body and tail are supplied by splenic artery branches. ant. = anterior, EIA = external iliac artery, IIA = internal iliac artery, post. = posterior. (B) Illustration of the donor-recipient arterial anastomoses, including the arterial anastomoses of the donor pancreas with the donor Y-graft and the anastomosis of the donor Y-graft with the recipient common iliac artery (dashed lines)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig1.jpg" height="2240" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Donor and recipient pancreas arterial anatomy, including the regional arteries (arrows) and the sites of surgical ligation for donor pancreas harvest and donor Y-graft harvest (dashed lines). <i>CIA</i> = common iliac artery. <b>(A)</b> The head and uncinate process of the native pancreas are supplied by the superior and inferior pancreaticoduodenal arteries, which arise from the gastroduodenal artery and SMA, respectively, whereas the body and tail are supplied by splenic artery branches. <i>ant.</i> = anterior, <i>EIA</i> = external iliac artery, <i>IIA</i> = internal iliac artery, <i>post.</i> = posterior. <b>(B)</b> Illustration of the donor-recipient arterial anastomoses, including the arterial anastomoses of the donor pancreas with the donor Y-graft and the anastomosis of the donor Y-graft with the recipient common iliac artery (dashed lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Recipient venous anatomy, with dashed line indicating the donor PV anastomosis with recipient common iliac vein (CIV). IVC = inferior vena cava."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig2.jpg" height="1068" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Recipient venous anatomy, with dashed line indicating the donor PV anastomosis with recipient common iliac vein <i>(CIV)</i>. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Exocrine drainage of the donor pancreas is from the main pancreatic duct into the donor duodenum through the donor ampulla of Vater and into the recipient small bowel through the duodenum–small bowel anastomosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig3.jpg" height="853" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Exocrine drainage of the donor pancreas is from the main pancreatic duct into the donor duodenum through the donor ampulla of Vater and into the recipient small bowel through the duodenum–small bowel anastomosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Pancreas allograft in a 51-year-old woman who underwent PT for type 1 diabetes. (A) Gray-scale US image shows normal homogeneous hypoechoic pancreas parenchyma compared with adjacent fat. (B) Color Doppler US image shows the patent Y-graft, splenic vein, and PV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig4.jpg" height="720" width="2099" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Pancreas allograft in a 51-year-old woman who underwent PT for type 1 diabetes. <b>(A)</b> Gray-scale US image shows normal homogeneous hypoechoic pancreas parenchyma compared with adjacent fat. <b>(B)</b> Color Doppler US image shows the patent Y-graft, splenic vein, and PV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="CEUS dual images in a 27-year-old woman on postoperative day 2 who underwent PT for type 1 diabetes. Gray-scale images show a hypoechoic PT (P) with normal uniform arterial enhancement of parenchyma at 12 seconds (red arrows) and expected washout by 90 seconds (white arrows). Note the PV enhancement (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig5.jpg" height="1603" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. CEUS dual images in a 27-year-old woman on postoperative day 2 who underwent PT for type 1 diabetes. Gray-scale images show a hypoechoic PT <i>(P)</i> with normal uniform arterial enhancement of parenchyma at 12 seconds (red arrows) and expected washout by 90 seconds (white arrows). Note the PV enhancement (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal CT appearance of PT in two patients. (A) Coronal noncontrast CT reformation in a 47-year-old woman who underwent simultaneous kidney and pancreas transplant for end-stage renal failure and type 1 diabetes shows the elongated homogeneous pancreas (P) in the right iliac fossa. Note the fluid-filled duodenal stump (D). (B) Axial CT image without intravenous contrast material in a 45-year-old man with PT shows the benefit of positive enteric contrast material, which distinguishes bowel from the PT (dashed outline). Also note the adjacent embolization coils (arrow) that help localize the pancreas after treatment of arteriovenous fistula (AVF). (C) Coronal arterial phase CT reformation in the same patient as in A shows avid homogeneous parenchymal enhancement. Venous phase images (not shown) showed gradual decrease of enhancement. Note the fluid-filled duodenal stump (D), which should not be mistaken for a fluid collection. P = pancreas."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig6.jpg" height="1462" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Normal CT appearance of PT in two patients. <b>(A)</b> Coronal noncontrast CT reformation in a 47-year-old woman who underwent simultaneous kidney and pancreas transplant for end-stage renal failure and type 1 diabetes shows the elongated homogeneous pancreas <i>(P)</i> in the right iliac fossa. Note the fluid-filled duodenal stump <i>(D)</i>. <b>(B)</b> Axial CT image without intravenous contrast material in a 45-year-old man with PT shows the benefit of positive enteric contrast material, which distinguishes bowel from the PT (dashed outline). Also note the adjacent embolization coils (arrow) that help localize the pancreas after treatment of arteriovenous fistula (AVF). <b>(C)</b> Coronal arterial phase CT reformation in the same patient as in <b>A</b> shows avid homogeneous parenchymal enhancement. Venous phase images (not shown) showed gradual decrease of enhancement. Note the fluid-filled duodenal stump <i>(D)</i>, which should not be mistaken for a fluid collection. <i>P</i> = pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal MRI appearance of PT in a 47-year-old woman (same patient as in Figure 6A and 6C). D = duodenum, P = pancreas. (A) Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows low-to-intermediate T2 signal intensity of the pancreas with a T2-hyperintense nonenlarged pancreatic duct. (B) Coronal noncontrast T1-weighted MR image shows hyperintense T1 signal of the pancreas. The duodenum is identified as a fluid-filled C-shaped structure that should not be confused with a fluid collection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig7.jpg" height="699" width="1749" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Normal MRI appearance of PT in a 47-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig6">Figure 6A</a> and <a href="#fig6">6C</a>). <i>D</i> = duodenum,<i> P</i> = pancreas. <b>(A)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows low-to-intermediate T2 signal intensity of the pancreas with a T2-hyperintense nonenlarged pancreatic duct. <b>(B)</b> Coronal noncontrast T1-weighted MR image shows hyperintense T1 signal of the pancreas. The duodenum is identified as a fluid-filled C-shaped structure that should not be confused with a fluid collection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronal ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram in a 42-year-old woman after PT shows the Y-graft and splenic artery as widely patent. The pancreas parenchyma (bracket) does not enhance well because of the intravascular nature of ferumoxytol, an iron-based contrast material. CIA = common iliac artery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig8.jpg" height="848" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Coronal ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram in a 42-year-old woman after PT shows the Y-graft and splenic artery as widely patent. The pancreas parenchyma (bracket) does not enhance well because of the intravascular nature of ferumoxytol, an iron-based contrast material. <i>CIA</i> = common iliac artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Proposed imaging algorithm for evaluation of PT. ± = with or without, IV = intravenous, OR = operating room."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig9.jpg" height="1100" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Proposed imaging algorithm for evaluation of PT. ± = with or without, <i>IV</i> = intravenous, <i>OR</i> = operating room.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Donor splenic vein thrombosis in a 32-year-old woman immediately after PT. Spectral Doppler US image shows an enlarged transplant splenic vein with hyperechoic thrombus (arrow) and lack of flow with spectral Doppler imaging, consistent with splenic vein thrombosis. This was subsequently confirmed on interventional radiologic venogram (not shown) and treated with catheter thrombolysis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig10.jpg" height="782" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Donor splenic vein thrombosis in a 32-year-old woman immediately after PT. Spectral Doppler US image shows an enlarged transplant splenic vein with hyperechoic thrombus (arrow) and lack of flow with spectral Doppler imaging, consistent with splenic vein thrombosis. This was subsequently confirmed on interventional radiologic venogram (not shown) and treated with catheter thrombolysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent thrombosis in a 35-year-old woman with prior PT venous thrombosis treated with stent placement who presented with pain and elevated lipase levels. (A) Dual-screen CEUS images show the transplant parenchyma (arrows) with retention of contrast material beyond 90 seconds, suspicious for venous insufficiency. P = PT. (B) Time-intensity curve provides quantitative visualization of lack of washout. CT (not shown) helped confirm stent thrombosis. The circle indicates the region of interest over the PT to generate the time-intensity curve."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig11.jpg" height="1522" width="2248" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Stent thrombosis in a 35-year-old woman with prior PT venous thrombosis treated with stent placement who presented with pain and elevated lipase levels. <b>(A)</b> Dual-screen CEUS images show the transplant parenchyma (arrows) with retention of contrast material beyond 90 seconds, suspicious for venous insufficiency. <i>P</i> = PT. <b>(B)</b> Time-intensity curve provides quantitative visualization of lack of washout. CT (not shown) helped confirm stent thrombosis. The circle indicates the region of interest over the PT to generate the time-intensity curve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Venous thrombosis in two patients. D = duodenum. (A) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 52-year-old woman who presented with nausea and vomiting after recent simultaneous kidney and pancreas transplant shows a filling defect consistent with thrombosis in the donor SMV (arrow). P = PT. (B) Coronal oblique ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram in a 42-year-old man after prior thrombectomy shows nonocclusive thrombus in the donor splenic vein (arrows) and thrombus in the SMV (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig12.jpg" height="846" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Venous thrombosis in two patients. <i>D</i> = duodenum. <b>(A)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 52-year-old woman who presented with nausea and vomiting after recent simultaneous kidney and pancreas transplant shows a filling defect consistent with thrombosis in the donor SMV (arrow). <i>P</i> = PT. <b>(B)</b> Coronal oblique ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram in a 42-year-old man after prior thrombectomy shows nonocclusive thrombus in the donor splenic vein (arrows) and thrombus in the SMV (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Arterial insufficiency of the PT in a 38-year-old woman with pancreatitis and diabetic ketoacidosis in the setting of immunosuppression medication noncompliance. Dual CEUS images show a heterogeneous pancreatic head (dashed outline) on the gray-scale image and focal nonenhancement centrally (arrowheads) on the contrast-enhanced image, which corresponds to necrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig13.jpg" height="702" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Arterial insufficiency of the PT in a 38-year-old woman with pancreatitis and diabetic ketoacidosis in the setting of immunosuppression medication noncompliance. Dual CEUS images show a heterogeneous pancreatic head (dashed outline) on the gray-scale image and focal nonenhancement centrally (arrowheads) on the contrast-enhanced image, which corresponds to necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Arterial thrombus in a 57-year-old woman who presented with increasing pain 10 days after simultaneous kidney (K) and pancreas (P) transplant. Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows occlusive filling defect (arrow) and abrupt cutoff in the donor SMA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig14.jpg" height="789" width="951" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Arterial thrombus in a 57-year-old woman who presented with increasing pain 10 days after simultaneous kidney <i>(K)</i> and pancreas <i>(P)</i> transplant. Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows occlusive filling defect (arrow) and abrupt cutoff in the donor SMA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Venous stenosis in a 33-year-old man after PT who presented with pain. (A) Spectral Doppler US image shows elevated velocities with narrowing of the vein that is consistent with stenosis at the main portal vein (PV) to recipient common iliac vein (CIV) anastomosis. (B) Axial ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram helps confirm the PV–to–common iliac vein anastomotic stenosis (arrow) seen on the US image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig15.jpg" height="1662" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Venous stenosis in a 33-year-old man after PT who presented with pain. <b>(A)</b> Spectral Doppler US image shows elevated velocities with narrowing of the vein that is consistent with stenosis at the main portal vein <i>(PV)</i> to recipient common iliac vein <i>(CIV)</i> anastomosis. <b>(B)</b> Axial ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram helps confirm the PV–to–common iliac vein anastomotic stenosis (arrow) seen on the US image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Arterial stenosis in a 35-year-old woman with a PT who presented with right lower quadrant pain. Spectral Doppler US image shows color Doppler aliasing and elevated velocity of almost 400 cm/sec at the anastomosis (arrow) of the Y-graft with the right common iliac artery (CIA)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig16.jpg" height="815" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Arterial stenosis in a 35-year-old woman with a PT who presented with right lower quadrant pain. Spectral Doppler US image shows color Doppler aliasing and elevated velocity of almost 400 cm/sec at the anastomosis (arrow) of the Y-graft with the right common iliac artery <i>(CIA)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Arterial stenosis in a 50-year-old man with a PT complicated by recent pancreatic leak that was treated with percutaneous drainage. Axial ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram shows severe narrowing (arrow) of the transplant Y-graft and donor external iliac artery (EIA) anastomosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig17.jpg" height="750" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Arterial stenosis in a 50-year-old man with a PT complicated by recent pancreatic leak that was treated with percutaneous drainage. Axial ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram shows severe narrowing (arrow) of the transplant Y-graft and donor external iliac artery <i>(EIA)</i> anastomosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Active hemorrhage in a 42-year-old man 2 days after PT (P) who presented with dropping hemoglobin levels. Color and spectral Doppler US image shows an arterial waveform in an area of active bleeding (arrow) into an echogenic peripancreatic fluid collection (*). Note the color Doppler aliasing of the involved vessel and associated soft-tissue bruit (arrowheads) on the spectral Doppler waveform, which indicates turbulent high-velocity flow. The patient was returned to the operating room and was found to have a large acute hematoma, with part liquid and clotted blood and several bleeding vessels that were cauterized or ligated."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig18.jpg" height="782" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Active hemorrhage in a 42-year-old man 2 days after PT <i>(P)</i> who presented with dropping hemoglobin levels. Color and spectral Doppler US image shows an arterial waveform in an area of active bleeding (arrow) into an echogenic peripancreatic fluid collection (*). Note the color Doppler aliasing of the involved vessel and associated soft-tissue bruit (arrowheads) on the spectral Doppler waveform, which indicates turbulent high-velocity flow. The patient was returned to the operating room and was found to have a large acute hematoma, with part liquid and clotted blood and several bleeding vessels that were cauterized or ligated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Active bleeding in a 33-year-old woman who presented with hypotension and hematochezia 4 days after PT. Coronal CT angiogram (A) shows intravenous contrast material pooling in the small bowel at the anastomosis (arrow), which increased in the venous phase (B). Note adjacent free fluid (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig19.jpg" height="834" width="1698" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Active bleeding in a 33-year-old woman who presented with hypotension and hematochezia 4 days after PT. Coronal CT angiogram <b>(A)</b> shows intravenous contrast material pooling in the small bowel at the anastomosis (arrow), which increased in the venous phase <b>(B)</b>. Note adjacent free fluid (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic appearance of PSA in a 58-year-old man with PT. (A) Color Doppler US image shows yin-yang appearance in the PSA (arrow), whereas spectral Doppler waveform shows the characteristic to-and-fro waveform caused by bidirectional flow in the neck of the PSA. (B) Coronal reformation from CT angiography shows a large enhancing PSA (arrow) that distorts adjacent anatomy. There is mass effect on the adjacent transplant pancreas causing a dilated main duct (arrowhead). Because of the size of the PSA, the origin was difficult to determine at CT angiography. Angiogram (not shown) showed that the PSA arose from the SMA artery limb of the transplant Y-graft. This PSA was treated successfully with coil embolization and covered stent placement."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig20.jpg" height="800" width="1948" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Classic appearance of PSA in a 58-year-old man with PT. <b>(A)</b> Color Doppler US image shows yin-yang appearance in the PSA (arrow), whereas spectral Doppler waveform shows the characteristic to-and-fro waveform caused by bidirectional flow in the neck of the PSA. <b>(B)</b> Coronal reformation from CT angiography shows a large enhancing PSA (arrow) that distorts adjacent anatomy. There is mass effect on the adjacent transplant pancreas causing a dilated main duct (arrowhead). Because of the size of the PSA, the origin was difficult to determine at CT angiography. Angiogram (not shown) showed that the PSA arose from the SMA artery limb of the transplant Y-graft. This PSA was treated successfully with coil embolization and covered stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="AVF in a 31-year-old man 6 days after PT complicated by reoperation on postoperative day 4 who presented for hematoma evacuation. (A) Spectral Doppler US image shows high-velocity low-resistance arterial waveform and color Doppler aliasing at the site of the sampling gate. (B) Ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram shows a large AVF (arrow) between the donor SMA and the donor SMV at the pancreatic head, with aneurysmal dilatation of the donor SMV. (C) Catheter angiogram during coil embolization of the arterial branches feeding the AVF shows aneurysmal dilatation of the fistula (arrow) and contrast material opacification of the vein at the same time as the arteries."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig21.jpg" height="1629" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. AVF in a 31-year-old man 6 days after PT complicated by reoperation on postoperative day 4 who presented for hematoma evacuation. <b>(A)</b> Spectral Doppler US image shows high-velocity low-resistance arterial waveform and color Doppler aliasing at the site of the sampling gate. <b>(B)</b> Ferumoxytol-enhanced MR angiogram shows a large AVF (arrow) between the donor SMA and the donor SMV at the pancreatic head, with aneurysmal dilatation of the donor SMV. <b>(C)</b> Catheter angiogram during coil embolization of the arterial branches feeding the AVF shows aneurysmal dilatation of the fistula (arrow) and contrast material opacification of the vein at the same time as the arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Rejection of PT, which can be difficult to diagnose at imaging because the findings can be subtle or nearly indistinguishable from the findings of pancreatitis. (A, B) Allograft rejection in a 41-year-old man 7 months after transplant. Gray-scale US image (A) shows subtle enlargement and heterogeneous hypoechoic pancreatic parenchyma (P) with peripancreatic fluid (arrows). Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image (B) shows parenchymal edema and peripancreatic fluid (*) and inflammation involving the right lower quadrant PT (P), proven to represent allograft rejection at biopsy. (C) Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image in a different patient shows enlargement of the pancreas (P) with surrounding high-T2-signal-intensity fluid (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig22.jpg" height="1200" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Rejection of PT, which can be difficult to diagnose at imaging because the findings can be subtle or nearly indistinguishable from the findings of pancreatitis. <b>(A, B)</b> Allograft rejection in a 41-year-old man 7 months after transplant. Gray-scale US image <b>(A)</b> shows subtle enlargement and heterogeneous hypoechoic pancreatic parenchyma <i>(P)</i> with peripancreatic fluid (arrows). Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(B)</b> shows parenchymal edema and peripancreatic fluid (*) and inflammation involving the right lower quadrant PT <i>(P)</i>, proven to represent allograft rejection at biopsy. <b>(C)</b> Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image in a different patient shows enlargement of the pancreas <i>(P)</i> with surrounding high-T2-signal-intensity fluid (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute rejection in a 43-year-old woman that was proven with biopsy results. Gray-scale US image obtained during biopsy of right lower quadrant PT shows the echogenic needle tip (arrow) aligned along the long axis of the tail and body."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig23.jpg" height="831" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Acute rejection in a 43-year-old woman that was proven with biopsy results. Gray-scale US image obtained during biopsy of right lower quadrant PT shows the echogenic needle tip (arrow) aligned along the long axis of the tail and body.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic" aria-label="Pancreatitis in a 42-year-old man who presented with worsening pain and distention 5 days after PT. (A) Gray-scale US image shows an enlarged pancreas (P) with mildly heterogeneous echotexture of the parenchyma and small peripancreatic fluid collection (arrow). (B) Subsequent coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked edema, inflammation, and mild decreased parenchymal enhancement of the transplant pancreas (P) with multiple associated peripancreatic collections (*), consistent with acute pancreatitis. Note the transplant kidney (K) in the left lower quadrant and adjacent mildly inflamed bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig24.jpg" height="797" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Pancreatitis in a 42-year-old man who presented with worsening pain and distention 5 days after PT. <b>(A)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an enlarged pancreas <i>(P)</i> with mildly heterogeneous echotexture of the parenchyma and small peripancreatic fluid collection (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Subsequent coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked edema, inflammation, and mild decreased parenchymal enhancement of the transplant pancreas <i>(P)</i> with multiple associated peripancreatic collections (*), consistent with acute pancreatitis. Note the transplant kidney <i>(K) </i>in the left lower quadrant and adjacent mildly inflamed bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic" aria-label="Peripancreatic abscess caused by peripancreatic hematoma that became infected in a 50-year-old man on postoperative day 4. (A) Color Doppler US image shows a heterogeneous hypoechoic avascular fluid collection (arrow) with echogenic retracting clot and echogenic locules of gas with posterior shadowing. (B) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a rim-enhancing abscess (arrow) that contains locules of internal gas (arrowheads). D = duodenum, P = PT."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig25.jpg" height="815" width="1799" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Peripancreatic abscess caused by peripancreatic hematoma that became infected in a 50-year-old man on postoperative day 4. <b>(A)</b> Color Doppler US image shows a heterogeneous hypoechoic avascular fluid collection (arrow) with echogenic retracting clot and echogenic locules of gas with posterior shadowing. <b>(B)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a rim-enhancing abscess (arrow) that contains locules of internal gas (arrowheads). <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>P</i> = PT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic" aria-label="Peripancreatic hematoma in a 50-year-old man after transplant. (A) Color Doppler US image shows avascular complex collection (yellow calipers) without evidence of active bleeding. The sonographic appearance of hematoma is variable and can include layering echogenic material, complex heterogeneous collection, reticular pattern of septations, and retracting clot, depending on the age of the hematoma. (B) Coronal reformation from noncontrast CT shows multiple hyperattenuating peritransplant hematomas (arrows). Patient underwent subsequent reoperation for hematoma washout and transplant splenic vein thrombectomy. D = duodenum, P = PT."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig26.jpg" height="798" width="1798" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Peripancreatic hematoma in a 50-year-old man after transplant. <b>(A)</b> Color Doppler US image shows avascular complex collection (yellow calipers) without evidence of active bleeding. The sonographic appearance of hematoma is variable and can include layering echogenic material, complex heterogeneous collection, reticular pattern of septations, and retracting clot, depending on the age of the hematoma. <b>(B)</b> Coronal reformation from noncontrast CT shows multiple hyperattenuating peritransplant hematomas (arrows). Patient underwent subsequent reoperation for hematoma washout and transplant splenic vein thrombectomy. <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>P</i> = PT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="Exocrine pancreatic leak in a 49-year-old man with persistently elevated amylase and lipase levels from the surgical Jackson-Pratt drain. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT 1 month after transplant shows a peritransplant collection (*) consistent with pancreatic leak. P = PT."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig27.jpg" height="824" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Exocrine pancreatic leak in a 49-year-old man with persistently elevated amylase and lipase levels from the surgical Jackson-Pratt drain. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT 1 month after transplant shows a peritransplant collection (*) consistent with pancreatic leak. <i>P</i> = PT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic" aria-label="Enteric leak detected at CT 3 days following reoperation for bowel obstruction in a 36-year-old man. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT shows hyperattenuating extraluminal oral contrast material (*) in a fluid collection (dashed outline) surrounding the small bowel–to–donor duodenum anastomosis identified by sutures at anastomosis (arrowheads). The findings are consistent with enteric leak."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig28.jpg" height="942" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span>. Enteric leak detected at CT 3 days following reoperation for bowel obstruction in a 36-year-old man. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT shows hyperattenuating extraluminal oral contrast material (*) in a fluid collection (dashed outline) surrounding the small bowel–to–donor duodenum anastomosis identified by sutures at anastomosis (arrowheads). The findings are consistent with enteric leak.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic" aria-label="Postoperative ileus in a 50-year-old man a few days after PT (P). Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT shows diffusely dilated fluid-filled small and large bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig29.jpg" height="920" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span>. Postoperative ileus in a 50-year-old man a few days after PT <i>(P)</i>. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT shows diffusely dilated fluid-filled small and large bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel obstruction in a 52-year-old woman after PT. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT with oral contrast material shows dilated segments of small bowel proximal to a transition point (arrow) caused by adhesions. Note the normal appearance of the transplant pancreas (P) and the fluid-filled transplant duodenal stump (D)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig30.jpg" height="942" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span>. Small bowel obstruction in a 52-year-old woman after PT. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT with oral contrast material shows dilated segments of small bowel proximal to a transition point (arrow) caused by adhesions. Note the normal appearance of the transplant pancreas <i>(P)</i> and the fluid-filled transplant duodenal stump <i>(D)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic" aria-label="Closed-loop obstruction caused by twisting of the duodenojejunal anastomosis in a 33-year-old man who presented with increasing distention and fevers 9 days following PT. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT with oral contrast shows a dilated fluid-filled donor duodenal C-loop (D) adjacent to the pancreas (P). Closed-loop obstruction was detected at surgery. A closed-loop small bowel obstruction, characterized by obstruction of a bowel segment at two ends, can be recognized by its U-loop or C-loop configuration and has higher risk of complications."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig31.jpg" height="718" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span>. Closed-loop obstruction caused by twisting of the duodenojejunal anastomosis in a 33-year-old man who presented with increasing distention and fevers 9 days following PT. Coronal reformation from contrast-enhanced CT with oral contrast shows a dilated fluid-filled donor duodenal C-loop <i>(D)</i> adjacent to the pancreas <i>(P)</i>. Closed-loop obstruction was detected at surgery. A closed-loop small bowel obstruction, characterized by obstruction of a bowel segment at two ends, can be recognized by its U-loop or C-loop configuration and has higher risk of complications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32" class="graphic" aria-label="PTLD in a 57-year-old woman 12 years after PT. Coronal reformation from noncontrast CT (A) shows hyperattenuating masslike thickening of the terminal ileum (solid outline in A) and adjacent abnormal mesenteric nodal conglomerate (dashed outline in A), both with hypermetabolic activity on the fluorodeoxyglucose PET/CT image (B). Biopsy showed PTLD."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240180/asset/images/rg.240180.fig32.jpg" height="852" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig32" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span>. PTLD in a 57-year-old woman 12 years after PT. Coronal reformation from noncontrast CT <b>(A)</b> shows hyperattenuating masslike thickening of the terminal ileum (solid outline in <b>A</b>) and adjacent abnormal mesenteric nodal conglomerate (dashed outline in <b>A</b>), both with hypermetabolic activity on the fluorodeoxyglucose PET/CT image <b>(B)</b>. Biopsy showed PTLD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240180&amp;id=fig32">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">White SA, Shaw JA, Sutherland DE. Pancreas transplantation. <em>Lancet</em> 2009;373(9677):1808–1817.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(09)60609-7">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19465236/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Pancreas+transplantation&amp;author=SA+White&amp;author=JA+Shaw&amp;author=DE+Sutherland&amp;publication_year=2009&amp;journal=Lancet&amp;pages=1808-1817&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS0140-6736%2809%2960609-7&amp;pmid=19465236">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Finger EB, Radosevich DM, Dunn TB, et al. A composite risk model for predicting technical failure in pancreas transplantation. <em>Am J Transplant</em> 2013;13(7):1840–1849.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/ajt.12269">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23711225/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A+composite+risk+model+for+predicting+technical+failure+in+pancreas+transplantation&amp;author=EB+Finger&amp;author=DM+Radosevich&amp;author=TB+Dunn&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=Am+J+Transplant&amp;pages=1840-1849&amp;doi=10.1111%2Fajt.12269&amp;pmid=23711225">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dholakia S, Mittal S, Quiroga I, et al. Pancreas transplantation: past, present, future. <em>Am J Med</em> 2016;129(7):667–673.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.amjmed.2016.02.011">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26965300/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Pancreas+transplantation%3A+past%2C+present%2C+future&amp;author=S+Dholakia&amp;author=S+Mittal&amp;author=I+Quiroga&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=Am+J+Med&amp;pages=667-673&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.amjmed.2016.02.011&amp;pmid=26965300">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Voutsinas N, Singh AP, Lewis S, Rosen A. Multi-modality imaging evaluation of the who